
How Git Works (Simple Explanation) 
Git is a tool that helps developers track changes in 
files and code.It works like a save history system for
 your project.

Think of it like a video game save points.
Every time you make progress, you save it. 
If something breaks, you can go back to an earlier save.

1️⃣ Repository (Repo)

A repository is the project folder where Git tracks your files.

Example:

my-project/
   index.html
   app.js
   style.css

When you run:

git init

Git starts tracking that folder.

2️⃣ Working Directory

This is where you create or edit files.

Example:

index.html

You write or modify the code here.

3️⃣ Staging Area

Before saving changes, you must tell Git which files to include.

Command:

git add index.html

This moves the file to the staging area.

Think of it like putting files in a box before shipping them 📦.

4️⃣ Commit

A commit is when Git saves the changes permanently.

Command:

git commit -m "Added homepage"

Git stores:

the file changes

who made them

when they were made

a message describing the change

5️⃣ Remote Repository

You can upload your project to a remote server like GitHub.

Command:

git push

This sends your code from your computer to GitHub.

6️⃣ Pull

If someone else updates the project, you can download the changes.

Command:

git pull

This updates your local files.

🔄 Simple Git Workflow
Edit Files
     ↓
git add
     ↓
git commit
     ↓
git push
     ↓
GitHub Repository
Example Workflow
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git push origin main

This:

Starts Git

Adds files

Saves them

Uploads them online

One-Sentence Explanation

Git is a version control system that helps developers track changes, save project history, and collaborate with others.

